{"ts":"2026-06-16T19:45:00+00:00","source":"evolve-strategy","mode":"hypothesis","strategy":"momentum_12_1","baseline":"momentum_12_1","universe":"watchlist","params":{"top_n":20,"sizing":"vol_target","target_vol":0.3,"max_leverage":1.0,"vol_window":20},"splits":[{"name":"IS","start":"2017-01-01","end":"2021-06-30","sharpe":0.466,"cagr":13.522,"max_dd":null,"exposure":0.796,"turnover":1.84},{"name":"OOS","start":"2021-07-01","end":"2026-06-16","sharpe":-0.591,"cagr":-0.845,"max_dd":null,"exposure":0.137,"turnover":0.43}],"decay":1.057,"fitness":-1.7,"gate":"reject","hypothesis":"Switching sizing from risk_based to vol_target (exposure lever) fixes the ~15% under-deployment and lifts OOS Sharpe on the watchlist","notes":"DIAGNOSTIC WIN, OOS REJECT. vol_target sizing fixed deployment WHEN names are held: IS exposure 15%->80%, IS Sharpe +0.47, IS CAGR +13.5%. BUT OOS exposure still ~14% because the bottleneck is SELECTION not sizing: positive-12-1-momentum empties the book in the 2022 bear and re-enters too slowly (12mo lookback) to catch the 2023-24 recovery -> OOS Sharpe -0.591 ~= risk_based baseline -0.592. Huge decay (1.057) is regime-driven (bull IS, bear+recovery OOS). CONCLUSION: on a 12-name book the lever that matters OOS is re-entry speed of selection, not sizing. Next: faster re-entry signal. Single split; sizing reverted to risk_based default.","run_id":"2026-06-16T19:45:00+00:00-momentum_12_1-28d2"}
